As a legitimate educational tool, the one-and-done is the equivalent of renting a Lamborghini to drive to your high school reunion.
Big-time college basketball does benefit from the star power of one-and-dones, but the college sport won’t crumble if the concept fades away.
Quick history lesson: Until 1971, the NBA wouldn’t sign a player until he was four years out of high school.
A great high school player had no choice but to go to college for four years.
More importantly, college basketball will be spared the embarrassment of exploiting teenage basketball players for fun and profit.